  "slug": "slow-cooker-lamb-curry",
  "title": "Slow-cooker lamb curry",
  "subtitle": "Shoulder of lamb in a rich, aromatic sauce, eight hours low.",
  "excerpt": "Diced lamb shoulder marinated in yoghurt and spices, then slow-cooked with onions, ginger, garlic and tomato for eight hours until meltingly tender. The sauce thickens as the yoghurt cooks down. Serve with basmati rice and naan. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Anglo-Indian slow-cooked lamb curry. The yoghurt marinade technique draws on North Indian mutton curry traditions as documented in Madhur Jaffrey's Indian Cookery (1982) and Camellia Panjabi's 50 Great Curries of India (1994).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lamb shoulder is the right cut for this. It has enough fat and connective tissue to withstand eight hours in a slow cooker without drying out; the fat bastes the meat from within, and the connective tissue dissolves into the sauce. The yoghurt marinade acts both as a tenderiser and as a thickener for the sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The optional overnight marinade improves the flavour and is worth it if you plan ahead. At minimum, marinate for two hours. The spice base is simple: the complexity comes from time, not from dozens of whole spices.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
